INSERT INTO databasenode VALUES(6909,'2021-07-20T12:20:41','2021-07-20T11:20:41',NULL,'2021-09-03T22:20:11','2021-09-03T21:20:11','does-the-blue-yeti-x-mic-need-a-pop-filter','publish','post','https://raddy.co.uk/blog/does-the-blue-yeti-x-mic-need-a-pop-filter/',NULL,'
<p><strong>No</strong>. It&#8217;s a personal preference. </p>



<p>When I started my YouTube channel I was originally using the Blue Snowball Ice Microphone. There was nothing wrong with it, but I was getting a lot of reverb in my tiny office. Not knowing much about audio I decided to explore other options and invest in a better microphone. I ended up getting the Yeti X and later on my dad helped me build two sound panels to help with the reverb.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="405" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-podcasters-desktop-1024x405.jpg" alt="podcasting" class="wp-image-6923" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-podcasters-desktop-1024x405.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-podcasters-desktop-300x119.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-podcasters-desktop-768x304.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-podcasters-desktop.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption>Image from bluemic.com</figcaption></figure>



<p>The Blue Snowball microphone was great, but not being able to block noise around me was a bit of a problem. Especially the reverb of the room. I used to put pillows and blankets all around me when I was recording to make the audio sound better (I actually still do that to further improve the sound). From experience, the Snowball can benefit from having a pop filter to eliminate the &#8216;popping&#8217; noises when you speak into the microphone. </p>



<p>When I ordered my new microphone I also purchased a pop filter that fits and it looks better than the big circular ones out there. I ordered the <a href="https://kit.co/RaddyTheBrand/computer-recording-gear/moukey-microphone-po" rel="sponsored nofollow">Moukey Microphone from Amazon</a> and I was excited to try it out. The Pop Filter fit&#8217;s perfectly on the Yeti X and on top of that it looks good. I was happy with the look, but the audio sound was slightly different. </p>



<p>The main issue that I had with this particular pop filter is that it blocks a lot of positives. It&#8217;s hard to explain, but the sound is a little bit smoother which I don&#8217;t personally like. I prefer the &#8216;Crisp and Modern&#8217; sound instead of it being super smooth. Considering that I haven&#8217;t had any problems with the microphone &#8216;popping&#8217; I decided not to use the pop filter. What I am trying to say here is that it comes down to a personal preference, considering that I haven&#8217;t had any problems using the mic without a pop filter.</p>



<p><em>By the way, one technique that you can use to avoid &#8216;popping&#8217; is to position the microphone a little off-axis to your mouth, so you don&#8217;t speak directly into the microphone.</em></p>



<p>I would assume that the software has a lot to do with blocking the &#8216;popping&#8217; as I used to get that problem on my Snowball. Just to mention, the Snowball did not come with the software, but you can do things in OBS or in post-production. I just want to be as efficient as possible when I record or sound crisp when I am on a live stream.</p>



<p>I started digging even more to see if I am wrong about the pop filter. I had a look at some of the adverts to see if they are advertising the microphones with pop filer and also I looked on YouTube to see how they are being used.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="405" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-music-makers-new-desktop-1024x405.jpg" alt="signing bule yeti x" class="wp-image-6926" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-music-makers-new-desktop-1024x405.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-music-makers-new-desktop-300x119.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-music-makers-new-desktop-768x304.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-music-makers-new-desktop.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption>Image from bluemic.com</figcaption></figure>



<p>The result was mixed. A lot of the podcasters and YouTubers don&#8217;t seem to be using pop filters. On the other hand, people that sing, seem to be using them from time to time.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="405" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-game-streamers-desktop-1024x405.jpg" alt="blue yeti x" class="wp-image-6927" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-game-streamers-desktop-1024x405.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-game-streamers-desktop-300x119.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-game-streamers-desktop-768x304.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/getting-started-game-streamers-desktop.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption>Image from bluemic.com</figcaption></figure>



<p>Another thing that I found was that some people were using Windscreen Foam Covers instead. That&#8217;s another option that I am yet to explore. Let&#8217;s have a look at what are the differences between pop filter and foam cover:</p>



<div class="wp-block-columns">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">Pop Filter</h2>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="243" height="227" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/blue-yeti-x-pop-filter.jpg" alt="blue yeti x pop filter" class="wp-image-6931"/></figure></div>



<ul><li>Let&#8217;s you speak into the microphone with decreased pressure</li><li>Prevents fast-moving air from going into the microphone</li><li>Blocks A LOT of positives</li></ul>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">Foam Cover</h2>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="243" height="227" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/blue-yeti-x-foam.jpg" alt="blue-yeti-x-foam" class="wp-image-6929"/></figure></div>



<ul><li>Removes the noise caused by fast-moving air and dampens high frequencies</li><li>Blocks ALL plosives (high end and low end)</li></ul>
</div>
</div>



<h2>Conclusion</h2>



<p>Some online articles suggest that Pop Filter or Foam Cover is a must. I personally think that this particular model pop filter affects the sound quality of the microphone. It&#8217;s not bad, but I just prefer it without.</p>



<p>It might be worth trying a premium pop filter to see the difference. I just don&#8217;t have one to try at the moment.</p>



<p>What is your experience with The Blue Yeti X Microphone? Do you use a pop filter or a foam cover? and what do you use it for? Let us know in the comments below.</p>
