INSERT INTO databasenode VALUES(6876,'2021-07-15T13:53:44','2021-07-15T12:53:44',NULL,'2021-09-03T22:20:56','2021-09-03T21:20:56','how-to-deploy-node-js-express-ejs-mysql-website-on-heroku-cleardb','publish','post','https://raddy.co.uk/blog/how-to-deploy-node-js-express-ejs-mysql-website-on-heroku-cleardb/',NULL,'
<p>In this article, we are going to create and deploy a very simple Node.Js, Express Application using EJS as our View Engine and ClearDB for our MySQL Database. Everything that we are going to cover here is using the FREE services as long as you are working on a personal project and you don&#8217;t need a huge database. You can always scale up if you wish to.</p>



<h2>1) Create Heroku Verified Account </h2>



<p>The first thing that you need is a <strong>Verified Heroku Account</strong>. Unfortunately, in order to verify your account, you will need to put in your Credit/Debit card details so you can add <strong>add-ons</strong> like <strong>ClearDB</strong> to your Account. </p>



<p>Once you have created a Heroku account and you have it verified login to the dashboard.</p>



<h2>2) Create New Heroku App</h2>



<p>Create a new Application by clicking the &#8220;<strong>New</strong>&#8221; button on the top right corner and then select &#8220;<strong>New App</strong>&#8220;.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="437" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-heroku-account-1024x437.jpg" alt="heroku account dahsboard" class="wp-image-6887" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-heroku-account-1024x437.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-heroku-account-300x128.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-heroku-account-768x328.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-heroku-account.jpg 1178w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Give your app a name and choose the region that is closest to you or the one where most of your users will come from. Once you are done, click the &#8220;<strong>Create App</strong>&#8221; button.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="532" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-heroku-create-app-1024x532.jpg" alt="heroku create application" class="wp-image-6888" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-heroku-create-app-1024x532.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-heroku-create-app-300x156.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-heroku-create-app-768x399.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-heroku-create-app.jpg 1181w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<h2>3) Install ClearDB MySQL</h2>



<p>To Install <strong>ClearDB </strong>Navigate to the &#8220;<strong>Resources</strong>&#8221; Tab on the main menu. Scroll down to <strong>Add-ons</strong> and use the search bar to look for &#8220;<strong>ClearDB</strong>&#8220;. Submit the form and you should have <strong>ClearDB MySQL installed</strong>.</p>



<p> </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="661" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-heroku-cleardb-1024x661.jpg" alt="Heroku Create ClearDB MySQL Database" class="wp-image-6889" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-heroku-cleardb-1024x661.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-heroku-cleardb-300x194.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-heroku-cleardb-768x496.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-heroku-cleardb.jpg 1185w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<h2>4) Get ClearDB MySQL Credentials</h2>



<p>To find your <strong>database credentials</strong> click on the &#8220;<strong>Settings</strong>&#8221; tab and then scroll down until you see the &#8220;<strong>Config Vars</strong>&#8221; section. Find the &#8220;<strong>Reveal Config Vars</strong>&#8221; button and then click on it. This will give you everything that you need to connect to your database. <strong>Copy and paste</strong> the code somewhere on a text file so we can use it later in this tutorial.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="420" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/4-heroku-cleardb-credentials-1024x420.jpg" alt="Heroku ClearDB Find Credentials" class="wp-image-6890" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/4-heroku-cleardb-credentials-1024x420.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/4-heroku-cleardb-credentials-300x123.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/4-heroku-cleardb-credentials-768x315.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/4-heroku-cleardb-credentials.jpg 1169w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>The <strong>config vars</strong> should look something like this:</p>



<p>mysql://<strong>b54966f5205365</strong>:<strong>9cbaa662</strong>@<strong>eu-cdbr-west-01.cleardb.com</strong>/<strong>heroku_b1791a6475f6a54</strong>?reconnect=true</p>



<p>We need to break this down and get the following details:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-table"><table><tbody><tr><td>Username</td><td>b54966f5205365</td></tr><tr><td>Password</td><td>9cbaa662</td></tr><tr><td>Host</td><td>eu-cdbr-west-01.cleardb.com</td></tr><tr><td>Database</td><td>heroku_b1791a6475f6a54</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="106" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-heroku-cleardb-credentials-1024x106.jpg" alt="Heroku ClearDB credentials explained" class="wp-image-6891" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-heroku-cleardb-credentials-1024x106.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-heroku-cleardb-credentials-300x31.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-heroku-cleardb-credentials-768x80.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-heroku-cleardb-credentials.jpg 1117w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<h2>5) Connect ClearDB to MySQL Workbench</h2>



<p><a href="https://dev.mysql.com/downloads/workbench/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener sponsored nofollow">Download MySQL Workbench</a> if you haven&#8217;t yet and open up the application. To create a new connection, click on the small plus icon shown in the screenshot below:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="661" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-heroku-mysql-workbench-1024x661.jpg" alt="ClearDB WorkBench" class="wp-image-6892" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-heroku-mysql-workbench-1024x661.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-heroku-mysql-workbench-300x194.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-heroku-mysql-workbench-768x496.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-heroku-mysql-workbench.jpg 1185w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>This will open up the <strong>Setup New Connection</strong> window and now we need to <strong>enter the credentials</strong> that we took from Heroku earlier in <strong>Step 4</strong>. Note that you can leave the Port to <strong>3306</strong>.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="842" height="546" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/7-heroku-mysql-workbench.jpg" alt="MySQL Workbench ClearDB details" class="wp-image-6893" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/7-heroku-mysql-workbench.jpg 842w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/7-heroku-mysql-workbench-300x195.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/7-heroku-mysql-workbench-768x498.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 842px) 100vw, 842px" /></figure>



<p>Once you enter the connection details make sure that you click &#8220;<strong>Test Connection</strong>&#8221; to ensure that everything is working well. If you get the Connection Successful message, click &#8220;<strong>OK</strong>&#8221; and this will save the MySQL Connection for us.</p>



<p>If the connection didn&#8217;t work, make sure that you go back to <strong>Step 4</strong> and <strong>double-check the credentials</strong> that you entered. </p>



<h2>6) Create User Test table</h2>



<p>In order to test this project, we will need at least one table. Let&#8217;s create a new &#8220;<strong>user</strong>&#8221; table where we can store our user data. To do this click on our newly created connection to enter the MySQL Workbench Dashboard.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="899" height="380" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/8-heroku-mysql-workbench.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-6894" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/8-heroku-mysql-workbench.jpg 899w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/8-heroku-mysql-workbench-300x127.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/8-heroku-mysql-workbench-768x325.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 899px) 100vw, 899px" /></figure>



<p>Now we need to find our database and create a new table. Find the &#8220;Schemas&#8221; Tab in the left sidebar and select it. You should be able to see your SCHEMAS there. <strong>Double click</strong> on your <strong>database </strong>and then create a new table by clicking the &#8220;new table&#8221; icon just under the Query menu shown in the image below:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="702" height="480" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-new-table.jpg" alt="MySQL ClearDB MySQL Workbench create new table" class="wp-image-6895" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-new-table.jpg 702w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-new-table-300x205.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 702px) 100vw, 702px" /></figure>



<p>This is where we can create our new &#8220;user&#8221; table. To make it simple, I am only going to add an id, name and a job column name just like the image above. </p>



<p>Alternatively, you can do the query manually if you wish to:</p>



<div class="wp-block-codemirror-blocks-code-block code-block"><pre class="CodeMirror" data-setting="{&quot;mode&quot;:&quot;sql&quot;,&quot;mime&quot;:&quot;text/x-mysql&quot;,&quot;theme&quot;:&quot;dracula&quot;,&quot;lineNumbers&quot;:true,&quot;styleActiveLine&quot;:true,&quot;lineWrapping&quot;:true,&quot;readOnly&quot;:true,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;Create user table&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;MySQL&quot;,&quot;modeName&quot;:&quot;mysql&quot;}">CREATE TABLE `heroku_4eb7a8ff5383ffb`.`user` (
  `id` INT NOT NULL,
  `name` VARCHAR(45) NULL,
  `job` VARCHAR(45) NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`));</pre></div>



<h2>7) Create user record</h2>



<p>To create a new record, expand your &#8220;<strong>Tables</strong>&#8221; in the left sidebar and hover over the table &#8220;<strong>user</strong>&#8221; which should show you a tiny grid icon on the right side. Click on it and that should open your user table and you should be able to see the columns and rows grid just like in the image below:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="580" src="https://raddy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-user-table-1024x580.jpg" alt="Creating User Table" class="wp-image-6896" srcset="https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-user-table-1024x580.jpg 1024w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-user-table-300x170.jpg 300w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-user-table-768x435.jpg 768w, https://g8b9j5b9.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-heroku-mysql-workbench-user-table.jpg 1146w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Enter at least one record. I have mine set to id: 1, name: Rad and job: Web Developer. Once you are done make sure that you apply the changes.</p>



<p>Our database is now ready and we can create a super simple application to test it out before we deploy it to Heroku.</p>



<p></p>



<h2>1) Creating Node.js, Express, EJS Application </h2>



<p>The first thing that you need to do is to create yourself a new project folder. Once you do that make sure that you open your Terminal. Command-Line or Powershell and CD to your project folder.</p>



<div class="wp-block-codemirror-blocks-code-block code-block"><pre class="CodeMirror" data-setting="{&quot;mode&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;,&quot;mime&quot;:&quot;application/x-powershell&quot;,&quot;theme&quot;:&quot;dracula&quot;,&quot;lineNumbers&quot;:true,&quot;styleActiveLine&quot;:true,&quot;lineWrapping&quot;:true,&quot;readOnly&quot;:true,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;Initialise a new project&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;PowerShell&quot;,&quot;modeName&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;}">npm init</pre></div>



<p>This will initialise a new project for you and its going to ask you a few questions about your project. The most important one is to give your package a name and then you can just keep pressing enter until the installation is over.</p>



<p>You can skip all questions by adding the &#8220;-y&#8221; flag like in the example below:</p>



<div class="wp-block-codemirror-blocks-code-block code-block"><pre class="CodeMirror" data-setting="{&quot;mode&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;,&quot;mime&quot;:&quot;application/x-powershell&quot;,&quot;theme&quot;:&quot;dracula&quot;,&quot;lineNumbers&quot;:true,&quot;styleActiveLine&quot;:true,&quot;lineWrapping&quot;:true,&quot;readOnly&quot;:true,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;Init a new project - skip questions&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;PowerShell&quot;,&quot;modeName&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;}">npm init -y</pre></div>



<p>If the &#8220;-y&#8221; flag doesn&#8217;t work for you, you probably have spaces in your project folder name or maybe even special characters. You can try without spaces and special characters.</p>



<p>At this point, you should see a file called package.json in your project folder.</p>



<h2>2) Dependencies Installation</h2>



<p>There are only three dependencies that we need for this project. We need Express, Ejs and MySQL. Express is going to help us create a server, Ejs is going to be our view engine and MySQL will help us connect to our database.</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">[x] express
[x] ejs
[x] mysql</pre>



<p>Open the Command Line / Terminal / Powershell and install the following dependencies:</p>



<div class="wp-block-codemirror-blocks-code-block code-block"><pre class="CodeMirror" data-setting="{&quot;mode&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;,&quot;mime&quot;:&quot;application/x-powershell&quot;,&quot;theme&quot;:&quot;dracula&quot;,&quot;lineNumbers&quot;:true,&quot;styleActiveLine&quot;:true,&quot;lineWrapping&quot;:true,&quot;readOnly&quot;:true,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;PowerShell&quot;,&quot;modeName&quot;:&quot;powershell&quot;}">npm install express ejs mysql</pre></div>



<p>Your packages.json file should look similar to this:</p>



<div class="wp-block-codemirror-blocks-code-block code-block"><pre class="CodeMirror" data-setting="{&quot;mode&quot;:&quot;javascript&quot;,&quot;mime&quot;:&quot;text/javascript&quot;,&quot;theme&quot;:&quot;dracula&quot;,&quot;lineNumbers&quot;:true,&quot;styleActiveLine&quot;:true,&quot;lineWrapping&quot;:true,&quot;readOnly&quot;:true,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;package.json&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;JavaScript&quot;,&quot;modeName&quot;:&quot;js&quot;}">{
